3. Evaluating ACF and PACF plots

ACF plot shows the significant correlation between current time series and previous lags. Typically, such assumption is appropriate when time series, represented by vertical lines, cross the level of significance (blue dashed line) just as it dispalys. Also, observation suggests presence of correlation between the last 3 terms, which makes the lag possibly equal to 3. Since time series drop gradually, there is an assumption of non-stationary data behavior. Versus, if there was a sudden drop it would point on the stationary data and zero correlation between lags.
PACF also suggests lag equal to 3, because of the first three vertical lines, that are above the 95% of significance level.
To verify above assumptions, adf.test() is performed. Null hypothesis is that data is non-stationary. Since p-value is 0.144 which is more then excepted 0.05, we fail to reject null hypothesis and have enough evidence to assume that the data is non-stationary. Adf.test() also recommends lag of 3, which confirms findings from the plots.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
# Modeling time series against Invoice Values per plots ACF
# and PACF
acf(as.ts(dataset[13:50, ]$TotalInv), main = "Sales")  #excluded years 2020 [52:54,] and 2016

5. Forecasting 4 months ahead using AUTO.ARIMA(0,1,1)(0,1,0)[12] and comparing to the fitted values

train_index <- 46
n_total <- nrow(dataset[13:50, ])
dataset_train1 <- (dataset[13:(train_index), ])  # training 1-46
dataset_test <- dataset[(train_index + 1):50, ]  # testing 47-50
predicted <- numeric((n_total + 12 - train_index))  #50-46=4
for (i in 1:(n_total - train_index + 12)) {
    dataset_train <- dataset[13:(train_index - 1 + i), ]
    arima.model <- auto.arima(ts(dataset_train$TotalInv))
    pred <- forecast(arima.model, 1)
    predicted[i] <- pred$mean
}
# Four Month Ahead Estimated Observed vs Predicted
df_1_1mo <- tibble(obs = c(dataset_train1$TotalInv, dataset_test$TotalInv), 
    predicted = c(dataset_train1$TotalInv, predicted), time = dataset[13:50, 
        ]$Date) %>% mutate(abs_error = abs(obs - predicted)/obs)


# Plot Four Month Ahead Estimation
A_1mo <- ggplot(gather(df_1_1mo, obs_pred, value, -time) %>% 
    mutate(obs_pred = factor(obs_pred, levels = c("predicted", 
        "obs"))), aes(x = time, y = value, col = obs_pred, linetype = obs_pred)) + 
    geom_line() + xlab("Years") + ggtitle("ARIMA(0,1,1)(0,1,0)[12]  Four Month Ahead Estimation")

# Fitted Observed vs Predicted
df_fitted1 <- tibble(observed = dataset$TotalInv[13:50], predicted = as.numeric(arima1$fitted), 
    time = dataset$Date[13:50]) %>% mutate(abs_error = abs(observed - 
    predicted)/observed)



fitted1 <- ggplot(gather(df_fitted1 %>% dplyr::select(-abs_error), 
    obs_pred, TotalInv, -time), aes(x = time, y = TotalInv, col = obs_pred)) + 
    geom_line() + xlab("") + ylab("") + ggtitle("ARIMA(0,1,1)(0,1,0)[12] Fitted") + 
    scale_color_manual(values = c("black", "hotpink")) + scale_x_date(date_labels = "%y %b", 
    date_breaks = "2 month") + theme_bw() + theme(legend.title = element_blank(), 
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 0.5))

# Two Plots and Tibble Together
grid.arrange(A_1mo, fitted1, nrow = 2)

tail(df_1_1mo)
tail(df_fitted1)

# Forecasting of 4 mo ahead arima1 Training and testing of
# arima1 model
train_index2 <- 46
n_total2 <- nrow(dataset[13:50, ])  #38
dataset_train2 <- (dataset[13:(train_index2), ])  # training 13-45
dataset_test2 <- dataset[(train_index2 + 1):50, ]  # testing 46-50
predicted2 <- numeric((n_total2 + 12 - train_index2))  #8
# Forecast ARIMA2 of 1 mo ahead
for (i in 1:(n_total2 + 12 - train_index2)) {
    dataset_train_2 <- dataset[13:(train_index2 - 1 + i), ]
    arima.model2 <- auto.arima(as.ts(dataset_train2$TotalInv), 
        xreg = cbind(as.numeric(dataset_train2$TotalUniqShipTos)))

8. Additional Forecast View on the Data

First ARIMA model (0,1,1)(0,1,0)[12] is still more appropriate because of lower AIC.
Moreover, second model changed its order since last analysis, even though number of observations stayed the same. Such change is not appropriate for the purpose of forecasting, since effective model need to be reliable.
Additionally, residuals of the second model seem to be NOT randomly distributed, but correlated. Such residual behavior suggests that assumption on randomisation would not hold, and model would not be sufficient in this case.

Training dataset represent the range of the time series from observation 13 to 42 inclusive and consists of 29 observations. The rest is the testing dataset representing last 8 month (December of 2019 to Jully of 2020).

The desired outcome is to have the black line (observed values) to stay within the shaded area, which indicates a proper model forecasting technique.

Observed actual values show drop in sales as expected during pandemic. In terms of forecasting this period may look like outlier, since business was impacted by third factor and it is not typical direction sales trend took.

Aside from deviation during pandemic times, predicted sales stay within 0.95 level of significance, which allows to chose first ARIMA model (0,1,1)(0,1,0)[12] as appropriate model for further forecasting.
